In article <jktaberCouIDC.8Bv@netcom.com>, jktaber@netcom.com (John K. Taber) writes:
|> David Sternlight (strnlght@netcom.com) wrote:
|> 
|> : No, the article was an example of irresponsible journalism, since the
|> : "rumor", if not made up out of whole cloth by the paper, is illogical on its
|> : face. Irresponsible media often make up stuff and attribute it to "rumors".
|> : Sometimes this is done to make their product more colorful, and sometimes
|> : just because they need something to fill space.  Responsible media do not
|> : publish rumors, and require two or three sources for what they do publish.
|> 
|> : David
|> 
|> This isn't crypto but I can't let this one slip by.  If the paper publishes
|> rumor, it is irresponsible; and if it does not publish rumor it is
|> responsible.  You have just described a tautology.  Papers are a lot more
|> complicated than that.
|> 
|> All papers publish rumors.  It just depends on whose.  They have ever since
|> the Fugger letters of the Middle Ages.  Yes, some papers check their
|> stories.  This consists of asking a few people a few questions.  Mostly
|> authority figures, like the police spokesman or the prosecutor.  Nothing
|> really searching.  They are publishing news, not research reports. 
|> 
|> Someday remind me to tell you about press releases.
|> -- 
|> John K. Taber                                 jktaber@netcom.com
